# .claudeignore — tells Claude Code which files to skip when browsing your project.
# Think of it as a "do not read" list. It's a starting point — add anything that
# feels private to you. For the strongest protection against secrets, fantasia setup
# also adds deny rules in settings.json alongside this file (see the note at the bottom).

# ── Secrets & credentials ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# These file types commonly hold passwords, API keys, and private keys.
# Claude Code will skip them when walking your project.
.env
.env.*
.env.local
.env.*.local

*.pem
*.key
*.p12
*.pfx

id_rsa
id_rsa.pub
id_ed25519
id_ed25519.pub

credentials
credentials.json
credentials.csv
*credentials*
*secret*
*token*
*api_key*
*apikey*

.aws/
.gcp/
.ssh/
secrets/

# ── Sensitive personal & business documents ───────────────────────────────────
# These patterns catch files that often contain personal or business information
# you probably don't want an AI reading. They're examples — tailor this list to
# your situation. If you have a folder called "financials/" or "client-docs/",
# add it here.
*tax*
*payroll*
*invoice*
*salary*
*medical*
*patient*
*diagnosis*
*prescription*
*ssn*
*passport*
*confidential*
*legal-hold*
*settlement*

# ── Local junk (wastes context, slows Claude down) ────────────────────────────
# These aren't secret — they're just large or irrelevant. Skipping them keeps
# Claude focused and faster.
node_modules/
.git/
dist/
build/
.next/
.cache/
__pycache__/
*.pyc
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
*.log
*.log.*
logs/
*.dump
*.sql.gz
*.csv.bak

# ── A note on how this works ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
# .claudeignore controls Claude Code's directory browsing — the files it finds
# when it walks your project looking for context. It does NOT prevent Claude from
# opening a file if it knows the exact path.
#
# For the strongest protection, fantasia setup adds Read deny rules in
# .claude/settings.json alongside this file. Those rules stop Claude's file tools
# from opening the listed paths even if asked directly. Together, the two controls
# cover the most common exposure vectors.
